A11y-dialog is a small, framework-agnostic helper to manage accessible modal dialogs.
It focuses on doing one thing well: enforcing a robust accessibility contract so that
keyboard and assistive technology users can reliably open, use and close dialogs
without getting lost in the rest of the page.

{% info %}
**Disclaimer:** a11y-dialog is less useful than it used to be due to the native
`<dialog>` element being now widely supported and generally consistent across
browsers. Read [the documentation](https://a11y-dialog.netlify.app/further-reading/dialog-element)
for more information.
{% endinfo %}

## What it does

- **Focus management**: traps focus within the dialog while it is open, restores
  it to the triggering element when it closes, and stays out of the way of
  native browser focus behavior.
- **ARIA wiring**: encourages using proper roles and relationships like
  `role="dialog"`, `aria-modal="true"`, and `aria-labelledby` without hiding
  complexity behind opaque abstractions.
- **Progressive enhancement**: starts from plain, semantic HTML and only adds the
  JavaScript needed to toggle dialog visibility and behaviour.

You provide the markup and the visual design; a11y-dialog takes care of the
accessibility details that are easy to miss or get subtly wrong.

## Using it

The project ships as a tiny, dependency-free script that can be used in several ways:

- Loaded directly in the browser and instantiated with vanilla JavaScript.
- Wrapped in framework-specific integrations such as `react-a11y-dialog`.
- Embedded into existing codebases as a focused utility rather than a full UI kit.

The [project website](https://a11y-dialog.netlify.app/) documents the public API,
recommended markup structure, and common patterns like multiple dialogs on a page,
nested dialogs, and custom open/close triggers.

## My role and motivation

I created a11y-dialog after repeatedly running into modal implementations that
looked polished but were unusable with a keyboard or screen reader. The goal was
not to invent a new design pattern, but to make the *correct* implementation of
the existing pattern easy to reuse across projects.

Over time, the project has grown with community feedback, bug reports and real
world usage across a variety of products and tech stacks. It remains deliberately
small and focused so that it can be audited, understood and adapted by people who
care about both user experience and accessibility.
